  "source": "Numerics/Mathematics/Linear Algebra/LUDecomposition.cs; the 3x3 case's matrix, rhs, and solution are scraped verbatim from Test_LUDecomposition.cs (Test_LUDecomp/Test_SolveVector/Test_Determinant/Test_Inverse); its determinant/inverse expected values were recomputed independently via exact rational arithmetic (Python fractions.Fraction, then converted to float64) rather than copied from the test's own (coarser, 1e-4-tolerance) literals, so this fixture's tighter 1e-9 tolerance has a trustworthy target.",
  "reference": "Numerics @ a2c4dbf. Each case's `target` selects the dispatch function (falls back to the file-level `target` if a case omits it -- mirrors fixtures/special_functions/cholesky.json). Convention: matrices are passed as flattened row-major doubles; n is inferred from the args length exactly as documented in cholesky.json (n = sqrt(len) for determinant; n = sqrt(len-2) for inverse_element, whose last two args are the (i, j) indices; n solves n^2+n+1=len for solve_element, whose args are [flattened n*n matrix, n-length rhs vector, index i]). Unlike Cholesky (symmetric positive-definite only), LU handles general square matrices, so both the 3x3 (scraped) and 2x2 (curated) cases here are deliberately NON-symmetric -- exercising the row-pivoting/permutation path that a symmetric-only fixture would never touch. The 2x2 case (A = [[4,3],[6,3]], b = [10,12]) was chosen for a clean exact solution (x = [1,2]) and recomputed the same way (exact rational arithmetic, then float64), and both cases' values were confirmed reproducible against the real C# LUDecomposition by tools/verify_oracles.py.",
